times found in the Gaelicized form <b>Pléamonn</b>.","German: variant of   Flemming  , cognate with 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Raoul","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Ralph</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"VI","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]},{"name":"Le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Lewis   or respelling of   Lou  , as borne by the impresario  Lew Grade  (  1906–98 , originally  Louis Winogradsky )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Raoul VI Le Flamenc was born as the son of Raoul V Le Flamenc and Helvide De Conflans. He had at least 1 son with Eleonore De Hangest. He died on 11 July 1302, in Kortrijk, West Flanders, Belgium."},"et":{"–11 July 1302":"–11. juuli 1302","–1302":"–1302","–Female":"Surnud","1288–1358":"1288–1358","–Male":"Surnud","1358":"1358","1302":"1302","1288":"1288","11 July 1302":"11. juuli 1302","Kortrijk, West Flanders, Belgium":"Kortrijk, West-Vlaanderen, Belgia","Noyelles-sur-Escaut,59159,Nord,Hauts-de-France,FRANCE,":"Noyelles-sur-Escaut, Nord, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"–11 July 1302":"–11. heinäkuuta 1302","–1302":"–1302","–Female":"Kuollut","1288–1358":"1288–1358","–Male":"Kuollut","1358":"1358","1302":"1302","1288":"1288","11 July 1302":"11. heinäkuuta 1302","Kortrijk, West Flanders, Belgium":"Kortrijk, West-Vlaanderen, Belgia","Noyelles-sur-Escaut,59159,Nord,Hauts-de-France,FRANCE,":"Noyelles-sur-Escaut, Nord, Hauts-de-France, Ranska"},"fr":{"–11 July 1302":"–11 juillet 1302","–1302":"–1302","–Female":"Décédée","1288–1358":"1288–1358","–Male":"Décédé","1358":"1358","1302":"1302","1288":"1288","11 July 1302":"11 juillet 1302","Kortrijk, West Flanders, Belgium":"Kortrijk, Flandre occidentale, Belgique","Noyelles-sur-Escaut,59159,Nord,Hauts-de-France,FRANCE,":"Noyelles-sur-Escaut, Nord, Hauts-de-France, France","lifeSummary":"Raoul VI Le Flamenc est né, fils de Raoul V Le Flamenc et Helvide De Conflans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Eleonore De Hangest. Il est décédé le 11 juillet 1302, à Kortrijk, Flandre occidentale, Belgique."},"de":{"–11 July 1302":"–11. Juli 1302","–1302":"–1302","–Female":"Verstorben","1288–1358":"1288–1358","–Male":"Verstorben","1358":"1358","1302":"1302","1288":"1288","11 July 1302":"11. Juli 1302","Kortrijk, West Flanders, Belgium":"Kortrijk, West-Flandern, Belgien","Noyelles-sur-Escaut,59159,Nord,Hauts-de-France,FRANCE,":"Noyelles-sur-Escaut, Nord, Hauts-de-France, Frankreich","lifeS